  <thing id="iS2IronBod" name="Ironwood Body" description="The plating used to build a warforged provides a +5, and you are considered to be wearing light armor. You now have a +5 maximum Dexterity bonus to AC, a -2 armor check penalty, and an arcane spell failure chance of 15%.  Unlike the other body feats, a warforged druid who takes ironwood body can cast druid spells and use the druid&apos;s supernatural and spell-like abilities.\n\nThis plating is not natural armor and does not stack with other effects that give an armor bonus (other than natural armor). This composite plating occupies the same space on the body as a suit of armor or a robe, and thus a warforged cannot wear armor or magic robes. Warforged can be enchanted just as armor can be. The character must be present for the entire time it takes to enchant him." compset="MagicArmor">
    <usesource source="srcRaOfEb"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="CustomItem" name="CustomItem" abbrev="CustomItem"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="Shadow" name="Shadow" abbrev="Shadow"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="NoSelect" name="NoSelect" abbrev="NoSelect"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="Helper" name="Helper" abbrev="Helper"/>
    <containerreq phase="GlobalTest" priority="0">TRUE</containerreq>
    <eval phase="Render" priority="99999999" index="2"><![CDATA[~ Do to the way the Material bootstrap changes the name we need to
~ add this line to make the name correct again.
field[livename].text &= " Body"]]></eval>
    <eval phase="PreLevel" priority="5000">~ Call magic armor gizmo
Call iMagArmor
~ Make us profcient with our own body
perform assign[Helper.Proficient]
~ Give us 2/Slashing DR
#applydr[xDamRdS,2]</eval>
    <child entity="gMagArmor">
      <tag group="Helper" tag="NoSelChild" name="NoSelChild"/>
      <bootstrap thing="mS2IronBod">
        <autotag group="Helper" tag="Forward"/>
        </bootstrap>
      <bootstrap thing="eIronwood"></bootstrap>
      </child>
    </thing>
  <thing id="fcFtrWarfo" name="Warforged Fighter" description="Add a +1 bonus on initiative checks." compset="FavClass" uniqueness="unique">
    <fieldval field="fcName" value="+1 initiative"/>
    <usesource source="S2Eberron"/>
    <tag group="FavClass" tag="cFighter"/>
    <tag group="IsRace" tag="rS2Warforg"/>
    <eval phase="PostAttr" priority="10000">field[abValue].value += field[fcCount].value
hero.child[Initiative].field[Bonus].value += field[abValue].value</eval>
    </thing>
  <thing id="raS2WarVul" name="Warforged Vulnerabilities" description="The unusual physical construction of warforged makes them vulnerable to certain spells and effects that normally don&apos;t affect living creatures. A warforged takes damage from {i}heat metal{/i} and {i}chill metal{/i} as if he were wearing metal armor. Likewise, a warforged is affected by {i}repel metal or stone{/i} as if he were wearing metal armor. A warforged is repelled by {i}repel wood.{/i} The iron in the body of a warforged makes him vulnerable to {i}rusting grasp.{/i} The creature takes 2d6 points of damage from the spell (Refl ex half; save DC 14 + caster&apos;s ability modifier). A warforged takes the same damage from a rust monster&apos;s touch (Refl ex DC 17 half). Spells such as {i}stone to flesh, stone shape, warp wood,{/i} and {i}wood shape{/i} affect objects only, and thus cannot be used on the stone and wood parts of a warforged." compset="RaceSpec">
    <usesource source="S2Eberron"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="ShowSpec"/>
    <tag group="SpecType" tag="Weakness"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="raS2WarDie" name="Die Hard" description="A warforged responds slightly differently from other living creatures when reduced to 0 hit points.  A warforged with 0 hit points is disabled, just like a living creature. He can only take a single move action or standard action in each round, but strenuous activity does not risk further injury. When his hit points are less than 0 and greater than -10, a warforged is inert. He is unconscious and helpless, and he cannot perform any actions. However, an inert warforged does not lose additional hit points unless more damage is dealt to him, as with a living creature that is stable." compset="RaceSpec">
    <usesource source="S2Eberron"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="ShowSpec"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="raS2WarCon" name="Consume" description="A warforged does not need to eat, sleep, or breathe, but he can still benefit from the effects of consumable spells and magic items such as {i}heroes&apos; feast{/i} and potions." compset="RaceSpec">
    <usesource source="S2Eberron"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="ShowSpec"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="rcWFBody01" name="Composite Plating" description="The plating used to build a warforged provides a +2 armor bonus. This plating is not natural armor and does not stack with other effects that give an armor bonus (other than natural armor). This composite plating occupies the same space on the body as a suit of armor or a robe, and thus a warforged cannot wear armor or magic robes. Composite plating also provides a warforged with a 5% arcane spell failure chance, similar to the penalty for wearing light armor. Any class ability that allows a warforged to ignore the arcane spell failure chance for light armor lets him ignore this penalty as well.\n\nWarforged can be enchanted just as armor can be. The character must be present for the entire time it takes to enchant him.\n\n{B}Note:{/b} With the Pathfinder changes this will now count as Light armor for all purposes meaning it will not work for a Monk character.  In such a case please take the &quot;Unarmored Body&quot; instead which will apply as NO armor." compset="RaceCustom" summary="+2 armor bonus and 5% spell failure." uniqueness="useronce">
    <usesource source="S2Eberron"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="SpecUp"/>
    <tag group="AllowRCust" tag="rS2Warforg"/>
    <bootstrap thing="iS2CompBod">
      <autotag group="Helper" tag="Displace"/>
      </bootstrap>
    <eval phase="First">~ Assign Body tag to hero
perform hero.assign[Warforged.Composite]
~ Assign Armored tag to hero
perform hero.assign[Warforged.Armored]</eval>
    </thing>
  <thing id="rcWFBody02" name="Adamantine Body" description="{i}At the cost of mobility, a warforged character&apos;s body can be crafted with a layer of adamantine that provides formidable protective armor and some damage reduction.{/i}\n\nThe plating used to build a warforged provides a +8 armor bonus and you gain damage reduction 2/adamantine. However, your base land speed is reduced to 20 feet, and you are considered to be wearing heavy armor. You have a +1 maximum Dexterity bonus to AC, a -5 armor check penalty, and an arcane spell failure chance of 35%.\n\nThis plating is not natural armor and does not stack with other effects that give an armor bonus (other than natural armor). This composite plating occupies the same space on the body as a suit of armor or a robe, and thus a warforged cannot wear armor or magic robes. Warforged can be enchanted just as armor can be. The character must be present for the entire time it takes to enchant him." compset="RaceCustom" summary="+8AC, +1 Dex, -5ACP, DR 2/adamantine, 35% spell failure." uniqueness="useronce">
    <usesource source="S2Eberron"/>
    <tag group="AllowRCust" tag="rS2Warforg"/>
    <bootstrap thing="iS2AdamBod">
      <autotag group="Helper" tag="Displace"/>
      </bootstrap>
    <eval phase="First">~ Assign Body tag to hero
      perform hero.assign[Warforged.Adamantine]
      ~ Assign Armored tag to hero
      perform hero.assign[Warforged.Armored]</eval>
    </thing>
  <thing id="rcWFBody03" name="Mithral Body" description="{i}Your body is crafted with a layer of mithral that provides some protection without hindering speed or gracefulness.{/i}\n\nThe plating used to build a warforged provides a +5, and you are considered to be wearing light armor. You now have a +5 maximum Dexterity bonus to AC, a -2 armor check penalty, and an arcane spell failure chance of 15%.\n\nThis plating is not natural armor and does not stack with other effects that give an armor bonus (other than natural armor). This composite plating occupies the same space on the body as a suit of armor or a robe, and thus a warforged cannot wear armor or magic robes. Warforged can be enchanted just as armor can be. The character must be present for the entire time it takes to enchant him." compset="RaceCustom" summary="+5 AC, +5 Dex, -2ACP, 15% spell failure." uniqueness="useronce">
    <usesource source="S2Eberron"/>
    <tag group="AllowRCust" tag="rS2Warforg"/>
    <bootstrap thing="iS2MithBod">
      <autotag group="Helper" tag="Displace"/>
      </bootstrap>
    <eval phase="First">~ Assign Body tag to hero
      perform hero.assign[Warforged.Mithral]
      ~ Assign Armored tag to hero
      perform hero.assign[Warforged.Armored]</eval>
    </thing>
  <thing id="rcWFBody04" name="Ironwood Body" description="{I}Your body is crafted with a layer of hard ironwood that cushions blows{/i}\n\nThe plating used to build a warforged provides a +3 armor bonus and you gain damage reduction 2/slashing, and you are considered to be wearing light armor. You have a +4 maximum Dexterity bonus to AC, a -3 armor check penalty, and an arcane spell failure chance of 20%.\n\nThis plating is not natural armor and does not stack with other effects that give an armor bonus (other than natural armor). This composite plating occupies the same space on the body as a suit of armor or a robe, and thus a warforged cannot wear armor or magic robes. Unlike the Adamantine Body and Mithral Body, warforged druids who take this feat can cast druid spells and use the druid&apos;s supernatural and spell-like abilites.\n\nWarforged can be enchanted just as armor can be. The character must be present for the entire time it takes to enchant him." compset="RaceCustom" summary="+5 AC, +5 Dex, -2ACP, 15% spell failure." uniqueness="useronce">
    <usesource source="srcRaOfEb"/>
    <tag group="AllowRCust" tag="rS2Warforg"/>
    <bootstrap thing="iS2IronBod">
      <autotag group="Helper" tag="Displace"/>
      </bootstrap>
    <eval phase="First">~ Assign Body tag to hero
      perform hero.assign[Warforged.Ironwood]
      ~ Assign Armored tag to hero
      perform hero.assign[Warforged.Armored]</eval>
    </thing>
  <thing id="rcWFBody05" name="Unarmored Body" description="{I}Your body is crafted without its normal layer of armor trading off physical strength for magical potential.{/i}\n\nYou lose the normal +2 armor bonus common to warforged characters, but you have no inherent chance of spell failure, do not count to be wearing armor, gain a +1 natural armor bonus and can wear armor or magic robes and gain their full effects." compset="RaceCustom" summary="+1AC and you can wear armor or magic robes." uniqueness="useronce">
    <usesource source="S2Eberron"/>
    <tag group="AllowRCust" tag="rS2Warforg"/>
    <eval phase="First">~ +1 Natural AC Bonus
      hero.child[ArmorClass].field[tACNatural].value += 1
      ~ Assign Unarmored tag to hero
      perform hero.assign[Warforged.Unarmored]</eval>
    </thing>
  <thing id="rS2Kalasht" name="Kalashtar" description="The kalashtar are a compound race: incorporeal entities from the alien plane of Dal Quor, the Region of Dreams, merged with human bodies and spirits to form a distinct species. They were once a minority among the quori, the native race of Dal Quor, hunted and persecuted for their religious beliefs. Thousands of years after the quori invaded Eberron and the connection between their plane and the Material Plane was severed, the kalashtar were the fi rst of the quori to discover a means to reach the Material Plane once more. Fleeing persecution, they transformed their physical forms into psychic projections that allowed them to enter the Material Plane and possess willing humans. Today, new kalashtar are born, not possessed; neither spirit nor human, they are a new race that breeds true.\n\nIt took three hundred years for the other quori to discover a similar means to psychically project their spirits out of Dal Quor and possess human bodies, forming the Inspired (see page 290), while leaving their own bodies behind - much as mortals project their minds to Dal Quor when they dream. For fi fteen hundred years now, the Inspired in their vast kingdom of Riedra have continued to persecute and oppress the kalashtar.\n\n{b}Personality:{/b} As a true hybrid of human hosts and quori spirits, the kalashtar possess keen intellects but are not ruled by logic. They seek the perfection of their minds and spirits, often to the exclusion of any physical pursuits.\n\nThey are generally warm and compassionate, but their manners and ways of thinking are alien to the native races of Eberron. They are more interested in psionics than in the magic that pervades Khorvaire, and often lace their discourse with esoteric terms such as &quot;matter,&quot; &quot;kinetics,&quot; and &quot;ectoplasm.&quot; The kalashtar are outcasts from their home plane and can never return there - not even in dream. The combination of life in exile and a dreamless existence makes the kalashtar slightly inclined toward madness, and some have speculated that the kalashtar devote themselves to psychic and physical discipline in order to keep themselves safely sane." compset="Race">
    <fieldval field="rGiveSpec" value="1"/>
    <fieldval field="rSpecSing" value="Ethnicity"/>
    <fieldval field="rSpecName" value="Ethnicities"/>
    <usesource source="S2Eberron"/>
